    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[GrRo99] Granville, Andrew and Roesler, Friedrich, The set of differences of a given set. Amer. Math. Monthly (1999), 338--344.",
      "remarks": "Erd\\H{o}s and Szemer\\'{e}di proved that\\[n^{1/2} \\ll h(n) \\ll n^{1-c}\\]for some constant $c>0$. The upper bound has been improved to $h(n)\\ll n^{2/3}$ by Freiman and Lev. A proof of these bounds can be found in a paper of Granville and Roesler \\cite{GrRo99}.\n\nGranville and Roesler also reformulate this problem as one in combinatorial geometry: given $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{Z}^d$ of size $n$ what is the minimum size possible of\\[\\{ \\delta(\\mathbf{a},\\mathbf{b}) : \\mathbf{a},\\mathbf{b}\\in A\\}\\]where $\\delta(\\mathbf{a},\\mathbf{b})$ has $i$th coordinate $\\max(0,a_i-b_i)$. Using this formulation they obtained improved lower bounds in fixed small dimension $d$.\n\nUsing this reformulation, ProofCouncil has proved that\\[h(n) \\leq e^{O(\\sqrt{\\log n})} n^{1/2},\\]and hence $h(n)=n^{1/2+o(1)}$."
    },
